<P>
My recent and planned work falls mostly into two broad categories:

<UL>
<LI>many-particle physics in ultra-cold 
trapped atomic gases;  
</LI>
<LI>applying techniques from <I>quantum information theory</I>
to study condensed matter
phenomena.
</LI>
</UL>

<P>
My research plans for the next few years are described briefly below,
in the <A HREF="#sec_plans-coldatoms">first</A> and <A
HREF="#sec_plans-QI">second</A> sections, arranged according to the
above two themes.  The <A HREF="#sec_relevance">last section</A>
points out the relevance and topicality of the research topics.

<P>

<H2><A NAME="SECTION00010000000000000000"></A>  <A NAME="sec_plans-coldatoms"></A><BR>
Planned research: cold atoms
</H2>

<P>
Some cold-atom topics I expect to work on, and corresponding research goals:

<P>
    *
<I>Non-equilibrium phenomena.</I>  
I will study:    
(1) evolution of many-atom systems after a sudden change of parameter.  (2) thermalization in isolated systems out of equilibrium.  
Of the first class above, I studied one example in a previous publication
[<A
 HREF="Plans_feb08.html#self_sweep_PRA05">1</A>], and another example is currently being addressed.

<P>
    *
<I>Vortex dynamics, rotating BEC's.</I>  
I will study:  
(1) dynamics of a few vortices and anti-vortices in trapped condensates
    [<A
 HREF="Plans_feb08.html#self_vortex-antivortex_unpubl">2</A>];  (2) vortex lattices and quantum Hall states in fast-rotating condensates of
    bosons and of fermion pairs.  

<P>
    *
<I>Pairing of polarized fermions.</I>  
Following my previous work [<A
 HREF="Plans_feb08.html#self_polarized_PRA06">3</A>,<A
 HREF="Plans_feb08.html#self_Rice_PRL06">4</A>,<A
 HREF="Plans_feb08.html#self_deformation_PRL07">5</A>], my goal is to understand (1) the equilibrium phase
diagram, (2) collective excitations, and (3) effects of a trap.

<P>
    *
<I>Designing and studying unconventional many-particle
states.</I>  
I will seek cold-atom realizations of states with topological order,
frustrated spin Hamiltonians, and states with unusual entanglement properties.

<P>

<H2><A NAME="SECTION00020000000000000000"></A>
<A NAME="sec_plans-QI"></A><BR>
Planned research: tools from Q.I. theory
</H2>

<P>
In recent years, concepts from quantum information (QI) theory, particularly
entanglement measures, have been found to be unexpectedly useful for condensed
matter systems.  In addition to providing novel characterizations of
unconventional condensed matter phases, there is the prospect of fashioning
QI-inspired concepts into useful tools and techniques for identifying phase
transitions and characterizing phases.
I plan to use a number of concepts from QI theory to study condensed matter
models and phenomena, and to develop these borrowed concepts into applicable
tools for condensed matter theory.
My goals are:

<P>
    *
<I>To study topological order in 2D using entanglement calculations.</I> 
<BR>(I will study both <B>fractional quantum Hall</B> states and spin liquids in
 <B>frustrated quantum magnets</B>, the two main contexts for topological
 order.)

<P>
    *
<I>To explore a variety of concepts and quantities from QI theory for
their utility in many-particle physics.</I> 

<BR> (I will use, <I>e.g.</I>, bipartite entanglement between unusual
partitions of many-body systems; multi-partite entanglement classes,
<I>etc.</I>, for characterizing many-particle phases and identifying
phase transitions.)

<P>
    *
<I>To develop efficient computational methods for entanglement measures in
many-particle models.</I>  
<BR>
(If entanglement measures are to be widely used for condensed matter, methods
for calculating them need to be available and well-known. I will focus on
specializing variational &amp; Monte Carlo methods for these new quantities.)

<P>
    *
<I>To seek and study nanoscience realizations for states with interesting
entanglement properties.</I> 

<br>
(Both solid-state and AMO realizations.)

<P>

<H2><A NAME="SECTION00030000000000000000"></A>  <A NAME="sec_relevance"></A><BR>
Relevance &amp; Topicality
</H2>

<P>
The field of cold atom gases is rapidly developing, with innovative new
experiments appearing continuously.  
Now that cold-atom experiments have moved into the realm of sophisticated
condensed-matter phenomena, studying cold-atom physics with a many-particle
perspective is particularly urgent.

<P>
Techniques from quantum information are likely to provide important new
methods for identifying phase transitions and describing phases.  Entanglement
measures have been utilized in the past five years for 1D condensed-matter
systems, and are only now being applied to the 2D case where exciting
unconventional phenomena occur.

<P>
This is clearly an exciting time to be working on these two dynamic and
fast-moving topics.  

